# Test Hygiene

Reference model: `secure-gate/tests/` is the canonical example of the preferred layout.

## Location and Structure

- Flat files by default. Single-concern tests use a flat `tests/{area}_tests.rs` file.
- Suite directories for multi-file groups. When a concern spans multiple sub-areas, use `tests/{area}_suite/` (e.g. `encoding_suite/hex.rs`, `encoding_suite/bech32.rs`).
- `mod.rs` inside a suite may only contain `mod` declarations, `use` imports, and `#[cfg]` feature gates. Never place `#[test]` functions in `mod.rs`.
- Flatten if only one module. Do not create a directory structure for a single file -- use a flat `tests/feature_tests.rs` instead.
- Inline `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` inside `src/` is allowed only for simple proof-of-concept tests tightly coupled to a reusable module. Complex or multi-step tests go in `tests/*.rs`.
- Separate binaries for isolation. Tests needing global state (custom allocators, `harness = false`, trybuild) get their own top-level `tests/*.rs` file.
- An `integration.rs` umbrella runner may aggregate suite modules via `mod` declarations when a single binary is preferred.

## Naming

- Flat test files: `{feature_or_purpose}_tests.rs` (e.g. `kdf_tests.rs`, `coding_agent_tests.rs`, `zeroize_tests.rs`).
- Suite directories: `{area}_suite/` (e.g. `encoding_suite/`).
- Test functions: `snake_case`, describe scenario and outcome. Pattern: `{type_or_feature}_{scenario}`.
  - Good: `fn fixed_try_from_hex_roundtrip()`, `fn encrypt_then_decrypt_roundtrip_succeeds()`
  - Bad: `fn test_encrypt()`, `fn test1()`

## Documentation

- Every test file opens with a `//!` module doc comment explaining what it tests and the testing strategy.
- Suite `mod.rs` files may use `//!` to summarize the sub-modules they aggregate.

## Redundancy

- No two tests should assert the same behavior with the same inputs. Use a helper, loop, or proptest for parametric variation instead of copy-pasting tests.
- Before adding a test, verify no existing test already covers the same contract.

## Known-Answer Tests (KAT)

- For crypto code, tests asserting against spec-sourced vectors must be clearly labeled with the source (RFC number, NIST document, or test vector suite name) in a `//!` or inline comment.
- KAT vectors must be in a dedicated file (e.g. `kat_tests.rs`) separate from property-based or unit tests.
- Do not invent test vectors -- use only published, independently verifiable sources.

## Property-Based and Fuzz Tests

- Use proptest or a similar property-based framework when a contract must hold for all valid inputs, not just sampled cases. Examples: roundtrip encoding, constant-time equality symmetry, type alias constructors.
- Use plain unit tests for specific contract assertions and known-answer verification.
- Place proptest suites in a `proptest_suite/` directory or a dedicated `proptest_tests.rs` file.
- Fuzz targets live under `fuzz/` (cargo-fuzz convention), not under `tests/`.

## Purpose

- Every `#[test]` fn must assert something meaningful. A test that calls a function without checking output or side effects is not a test.
- Tests must fail when the contract they verify is broken.
- Prefer `fn my_test() -> Result<(), MyError>` signatures over `unwrap()`/`expect()` in test bodies. Result-returning tests produce better failure output and compose naturally with `?`.
- Avoid `#[should_panic]`. It passes even when the wrong panic fires. Prefer asserting the specific error variant instead, or use `assert!(std::panic::catch_unwind(...).is_err())` only when the panic text must be validated.
- `#[ignore]` must have a comment directly above it explaining why the test is ignored and, where applicable, a reference to a tracking issue. Uncommented `#[ignore]` is forbidden.

## Shared Helpers

- Common fixtures, builders, and assertion helpers belong in `tests/common.rs`, not duplicated across files.
- `common.rs` re-exports and helpers are available to suite submodules via the umbrella runner.

## Compile-Fail Tests

- Use a `tests/compile-fail/` directory with trybuild to verify type-safety invariants are enforced at compile time.
- Each compile-fail source has a matching `.stderr` golden file.
- A driver file (`compile_fail_tests.rs`) runs the trybuild suite.

## Feature-Gated Tests

- Tests requiring optional features must be gated with `#[cfg(feature = "...")]` so `cargo test` without those features does not fail.
- Suite `mod.rs` is the natural place to apply feature gates to entire sub-suites.

## Test Isolation

- No test may depend on execution order or shared mutable global state with other tests.
- Tests requiring a custom global allocator or `harness = false` must be in their own top-level `tests/*.rs` binary, declared in `Cargo.toml`.

## MSRV Enforcement

- If a crate or workspace declares `rust-version` in `Cargo.toml`, all test, clippy, and doc runs must use the MSRV toolchain, not the latest stable.
- Use `cargo +{msrv} test`, `cargo +{msrv} clippy`, `cargo +{msrv} doc` explicitly.
- Never update `Cargo.lock` with a toolchain newer than the MSRV -- this can introduce lockfile formats unreadable by the MSRV compiler.
- CI must run tests on the pinned MSRV toolchain as a required job, not just on stable.

## Required Test and Clippy Invocations

When running tests or clippy on a crate with features, all of the following must pass and any issues found must be fixed:

```
# Test with default features (includes doctests and integration tests)
cargo test --doc --tests

# Test with all features enabled
cargo test --all-features --doc --tests

# Test with no default features (verifies minimal build)
cargo test --no-default-features --tests

# Clippy with default features
cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings

# Clippy with all features
cargo clippy --all-features --all-targets -- -D warnings

# Clippy with no default features
cargo clippy --no-default-features --all-targets -- -D warnings
```

- `--doc` ensures doctests compile and run correctly across feature combinations.
- `--all-targets` (preferred over `--tests` for clippy) covers lib, bins, examples, benches, and integration tests in a single pass.
- `--no-default-features` catches missing `#[cfg(feature = "...")]` guards on feature-dependent code.
- Fix all issues that arise from these runs; do not suppress warnings with `#[allow(...)]` unless there is an explicit documented justification.

Also required:

```
# Verify doc generation and intra-doc link resolution
cargo doc --no-deps

# For crypto and memory-sensitive code, run Miri on critical test paths
cargo +nightly miri test
```

- `cargo doc --no-deps` catches broken intra-doc links and missing doc sections that `--doc` in `cargo test` alone does not catch.
- `cargo miri test` catches use-after-free, uninitialized reads, stacked borrows violations, and undefined behavior that regular tests miss. Run at minimum on the core crypto and zeroization test paths.
